2 egg whites
pinch of salt
200 g powdered sugar
2 tsp vanilla sugar
1 tsp lemon zest
1 tsp orange zest
1-2 tsp cinnamon
150 g ground almonds
150 g ground hazelnuts
150 g ground hazelnuts + almonds

Beat egg whites with a pinch of salt until stiff peaks form
Meanwhile, sift the powdered sugar
Gradually add the powdered sugar to the egg whites. Beat for another 2-3 minutes
Spoon about 5 heaped tbsp of the meringue into the piping bag. Refrigerate until needed.
Add to the remaining meringue: vanilla, lemon zest, orange zest, cinnamon and 150 g ground almonds, 150 g ground hazelnuts. Mix until well-combined.
Knead the dough
Gradually add another 150 g ground hazelnuts/almonds mix to make a firm, barely sticky dough.
Note: too much nuts or the addition of flour can make the cinnamon stars hard.
Wrap dough into cling film and refrigerate for at least an hour or overnight.

Lightly dust the work surface with sugar before rolling out the dough.
Roll out the dough to about 1 cm thick.
Dip the cookie cutter into powdered sugar before cutting the cookies. 
Plsce cookies on a baking sheet lined with parchment paper.

Perfect cinnamon star should be baked on the outside snd soft and moist in the core. Icing should be white.

Bake unglazed stars at 120C, top/bottom heat for 10-15 minutes.
Cool the cookies. 
Glaze with the meringue on top. 
Bake the cookies on the lowest rack for 10-15 minutes.

